WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.368 --> 00:00:03.570
♪ ♪

00:00:15.915 --> 00:00:17.250
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Tonight...

00:00:17.317 --> 00:00:18.251
&gt;&gt; The trade tensions
are flaring up

00:00:18.318 --> 00:00:19.619
between the U.S. and China.

00:00:19.686 --> 00:00:20.786
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: With President
Trump upping the pressure

00:00:20.853 --> 00:00:22.221
for a trade deal with China...

00:00:22.288 --> 00:00:24.290
&gt;&gt; President Trump announcing
plans to increase tariffs

00:00:24.357 --> 00:00:27.827
on billions of dollars worth
of Chinese goods...

00:00:27.894 --> 00:00:29.261
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: "Frontline"
and NPR correspondent

00:00:29.328 --> 00:00:31.264
Laura Sullivan investigate...

00:00:31.330 --> 00:00:33.933
&gt;&gt; China is going to be number
one market

00:00:33.999 --> 00:00:35.869
from any perspective.

00:00:35.935 --> 00:00:37.103
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: For G.E.
or for everybody?

00:00:37.170 --> 00:00:38.437
&gt;&gt; For everybody.

00:00:38.504 --> 00:00:40.139
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: ...the forces
behind the conflict...

00:00:40.206 --> 00:00:42.609
&gt;&gt; We're not in a trade war;
we're in a techonomic war.

00:00:42.675 --> 00:00:44.377
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: ...both here and
abroad...

00:00:44.443 --> 00:00:46.145
&gt;&gt; This is a great power
struggle.

00:00:46.212 --> 00:00:48.314
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Do you think that
Americans should be worried?

00:00:48.381 --> 00:00:50.616
&gt;&gt; Oh, yes, I think so.

00:00:50.683 --> 00:00:52.318
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR:
...and what's at stake.

00:00:52.385 --> 00:00:54.253
&gt;&gt; Tariffs announced
by the Trump administration.

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:56.256
&gt;&gt; China is now punching back.

00:00:56.322 --> 00:00:59.091
&gt;&gt; China has a ten-year,
a 20-year, a 50-year plan.

00:00:59.158 --> 00:01:00.560
&gt;&gt; They've outsmarted us.

00:01:00.626 --> 00:01:02.428
They've done some things
that we don't agree with.

00:01:02.495 --> 00:01:04.497
We've got to fix our system
to compete with China.

00:01:04.564 --> 00:01:07.433
&gt;&gt; We do have a chance to see
the new cold war.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:09.902
I think it's a comprehensive
confrontation.

00:01:09.969 --> 00:01:11.304
That's dangerous.

00:01:11.371 --> 00:01:12.838
&gt;&gt; NARRATOR: Tonight on
"Frontline,"

00:01:12.905 --> 00:01:14.707
"Trump's Trade War."

00:01:18.111 --> 00:01:23.283
♪ ♪

00:01:36.028 --> 00:01:38.897
&gt;&gt; Wow, that's great. Yay!

00:01:38.964 --> 00:01:40.566
&gt;&gt; Air Force One landing

00:01:40.633 --> 00:01:42.735
at the Palm Beach International
Airport.

00:01:42.802 --> 00:01:45.204
&gt;&gt; LAURA SULLIVAN:
In April 2017,

00:01:45.271 --> 00:01:47.273
President Trump headed
to Mar-a-Lago

00:01:47.339 --> 00:01:49.075
for the most important
diplomatic meeting

00:01:49.142 --> 00:01:51.044 line:0%
of his early presidency.

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:53.078 line:0%
&gt;&gt; The key to Mar-a-Lago is,
once Trump got there,

00:01:53.145 --> 00:01:55.247 line:0%
as often he does, he finally
focused on the schedule.

00:01:55.314 --> 00:01:56.648 line:0%
&gt;&gt; A very large delegation

00:01:56.715 --> 00:02:00.186 line:0%
of almost every relevant Cabinet
member...

00:02:00.252 --> 00:02:01.721 line:0%
&gt;&gt; And said, "Hey, why are we
having these big meetings?

00:02:01.787 --> 00:02:04.891 line:0%
I want to spend as much
one-on-one time as possible."

00:02:04.957 --> 00:02:07.293
&gt;&gt; First one president arrives,
and then another.

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:09.629
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Within hours,
President Xi of China

00:02:09.696 --> 00:02:12.765
was on the ground,
bringing together the leaders

00:02:12.832 --> 00:02:15.802
of the world's two largest
economies.

00:02:15.868 --> 00:02:17.203
&gt;&gt; One of the things that
President Trump believes--

00:02:17.270 --> 00:02:19.105
he believes in this totally--

00:02:19.172 --> 00:02:21.808
is that personal relationships
of great powers

00:02:21.874 --> 00:02:23.475
can make a difference.

00:02:23.542 --> 00:02:25.711
&gt;&gt; The presidents face-to-face
for the first time.

00:02:25.778 --> 00:02:29.082
(cameras clicking)

00:02:29.148 --> 00:02:31.450
&gt;&gt; Thank you, everybody.
Thank you.

00:02:31.517 --> 00:02:34.754 line:0%
&gt;&gt; There was a lot of time in
the schedule with them

00:02:34.821 --> 00:02:38.023 line:0%
literally one-on-one,
being together

00:02:38.090 --> 00:02:42.127 line:0%
and creating the relationship
that the, the two big economies

00:02:42.194 --> 00:02:44.497 line:0%
needed to have with each other.

00:02:44.563 --> 00:02:46.699
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The leaders seemed
to connect.

00:02:46.766 --> 00:02:48.534
And so did the families.

00:02:48.601 --> 00:02:51.337
&gt;&gt; We wanted to make you feel at
home.

00:02:51.404 --> 00:02:53.506
&gt;&gt; Nihao.
&gt;&gt; Nihao.

00:02:53.572 --> 00:02:55.207
&gt;&gt; Hello, how are you?

00:02:55.274 --> 00:02:57.510
&gt;&gt; That summit was important,

00:02:57.577 --> 00:02:59.912
because the two leaders
established

00:02:59.979 --> 00:03:03.916
a strong personal relationship.

00:03:03.983 --> 00:03:08.454
I think the image is that
the two leaders sit together,

00:03:08.521 --> 00:03:11.724
and two family actually sit
together.

00:03:11.791 --> 00:03:14.060
President Xi and his wife
had a very good interaction

00:03:14.126 --> 00:03:15.761
with President Trump.

00:03:15.828 --> 00:03:19.598
&gt;&gt; We've had a long discussion
already,

00:03:19.665 --> 00:03:24.804
and so far, I have gotten
nothing, absolutely nothing.

00:03:24.871 --> 00:03:27.706
But we have developed a
friendship, I can see that.

00:03:27.773 --> 00:03:30.209
&gt;&gt; Come on, thank you,
thank you.

00:03:30.275 --> 00:03:32.412 line:0%
&gt;&gt; We say, "Okay, you see,
President Trump is a president

00:03:32.478 --> 00:03:37.550 line:0%
that we can work with, and he is
someone that we can talk to.

00:03:37.617 --> 00:03:39.585 line:0%
He's a reasonable leader,

00:03:39.652 --> 00:03:41.153
and maybe he can do something

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:45.124
the ordinary conventional U.S.
leader won't do."

00:03:45.191 --> 00:03:49.529
So the expectation was very
high, and the hope was,

00:03:49.596 --> 00:03:51.664
maybe they can control
the situation

00:03:51.731 --> 00:03:55.034
and they can work together
to solve the problem gradually.

00:03:55.101 --> 00:03:57.035
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:03:57.102 --> 00:03:58.270
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But long-standing
problems

00:03:58.337 --> 00:04:00.806
between the countries were
reaching a crisis.

00:04:00.873 --> 00:04:05.511
And despite the promising start
and all the optimism...

00:04:05.577 --> 00:04:07.479
&gt;&gt; I believe lots of very
potentially bad problems

00:04:07.546 --> 00:04:09.481
will be going away.

00:04:09.548 --> 00:04:11.951
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: ...within a year,
Trump would turn on Xi,

00:04:12.018 --> 00:04:14.820
imposing billions of dollars
in tariffs

00:04:14.887 --> 00:04:19.158
and leading the United States
into a perilous confrontation.

00:04:19.225 --> 00:04:22.962
&gt;&gt; The fights were nasty
that came out of Mar-a-Lago.

00:04:23.029 --> 00:04:26.198
The most intense fights and
debates in the White House

00:04:26.265 --> 00:04:29.101
were about this issue
of tariffs,

00:04:29.168 --> 00:04:32.705
but tariffs as a proxy
to the great economic war

00:04:32.771 --> 00:04:33.839
with China that
we're engaged in.

00:04:33.906 --> 00:04:35.407
There's no middle ground.

00:04:35.474 --> 00:04:37.076
One side's going to win,
and one side's going to lose.

00:04:37.143 --> 00:04:38.711
And so we knew the stakes
were high.

00:04:38.778 --> 00:04:41.447
♪ ♪

00:04:41.514 --> 00:04:43.416
(cameras clicking)

00:04:56.028 --> 00:04:58.998 line:0%
&gt;&gt; On the frontline of the
rapidly escalating trade war,

00:04:59.065 --> 00:05:01.367 line:0%
American companies are bracing
for battle.

00:05:01.433 --> 00:05:04.703 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Last fall, I headed
to southwestern Ohio.

00:05:04.770 --> 00:05:07.773 line:0%
President Trump had fired the
first shots in his trade war

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:11.544 line:0%
with tariffs on a wide array of
imported Chinese goods,

00:05:11.611 --> 00:05:14.613 line:0%
from electronics to furniture
to steel.

00:05:14.680 --> 00:05:16.916 line:0%
&gt;&gt; President Trump turns up the
heat on China.

00:05:16.982 --> 00:05:19.518 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: I wanted to see
first-hand how these tariffs

00:05:19.585 --> 00:05:20.919 line:0%
were playing out on the ground.

00:05:20.986 --> 00:05:23.489 line:0%
&gt;&gt; As things come to a boiling
point between the two largest

00:05:23.556 --> 00:05:25.224 line:0%
economies in the world,

00:05:25.291 --> 00:05:27.159 line:0%
tariffs are now hitting
too close too home.

00:05:27.226 --> 00:05:29.395 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Trump claimed the
tariffs would help

00:05:29.462 --> 00:05:32.198 line:0%
American workers,
boost U.S. businesses,

00:05:32.265 --> 00:05:34.967 line:0%
and bring life back to places
like this,

00:05:35.034 --> 00:05:37.503 line:0%
which for decades had been hurt
by automation

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:40.672 line:0%
and, more recently,
imports from China.

00:05:40.739 --> 00:05:43.176 line:0%
&gt;&gt; President Trump says he's
keeping a campaign promise

00:05:43.242 --> 00:05:45.511 line:0%
to bring back
steel-industry jobs.

00:05:46.579 --> 00:05:48.080
&gt;&gt; On the streets of Middletown,

00:05:48.147 --> 00:05:50.583
the signs of economic struggle
are everywhere.

00:05:50.650 --> 00:05:52.184
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The tariffs on
imported steel

00:05:52.251 --> 00:05:55.087
were particularly welcome news
to struggling communities

00:05:55.154 --> 00:05:58.090
like Middletown, where I met up
with some steelworkers

00:05:58.157 --> 00:06:00.325
at a local coffee shop.

00:06:00.392 --> 00:06:02.195
&gt;&gt; There used to be a mall down
here.

00:06:02.261 --> 00:06:04.263
We had three city parks and
three city pools,

00:06:04.329 --> 00:06:06.165
and now there's none.

00:06:06.232 --> 00:06:07.667 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What did you think
when you first heard

00:06:07.734 --> 00:06:09.835 line:0%
that Trump was putting tariffs
on steel?

00:06:09.902 --> 00:06:11.971 line:0%
&gt;&gt; I thought it was, you know,
it was about time.

00:06:12.037 --> 00:06:14.840 line:0%
I've watched the, the farmers
get their subsidies.

00:06:14.906 --> 00:06:18.310 line:0%
I've watched the banks bailout,
the automotive-industry bailout,

00:06:18.377 --> 00:06:20.312 line:0%
and I've just watched us
wither on the vine

00:06:20.379 --> 00:06:21.581 line:0%
for the last 30 years.

00:06:21.647 --> 00:06:23.049 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Do you think it's
going to help the town?

00:06:23.116 --> 00:06:24.850 line:0%
Do you think it's going to help
your hometowns?

00:06:24.916 --> 00:06:26.853 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Sure.
&gt;&gt; Absolutely.

00:06:26.919 --> 00:06:28.354 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What are you
expecting to see?

00:06:28.421 --> 00:06:29.889 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Everybody always talks about
jobs and America,

00:06:29.956 --> 00:06:31.423 line:0%
and we hear that all the time.

00:06:31.490 --> 00:06:33.959 line:0%
We want to see that, that
reality happen.

00:06:34.026 --> 00:06:37.797
You know, you can't just depend
on foreign countries

00:06:37.864 --> 00:06:39.431
for, for steel.

00:06:39.498 --> 00:06:40.999
We've got to make it in
the United States.

00:06:41.066 --> 00:06:43.136
&gt;&gt; We just want China to play
by the rules.

00:06:43.202 --> 00:06:44.303
&gt;&gt; Right.
&gt;&gt; That's it.

00:06:44.369 --> 00:06:45.905
We don't, we don't want
a bailout.

00:06:45.972 --> 00:06:48.141 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: So you're saying
it's not that you want

00:06:48.207 --> 00:06:50.909 line:0%
your industry propped up?
&gt;&gt; No, not at all.

00:06:50.976 --> 00:06:52.544 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: You want your
industry...

00:06:52.611 --> 00:06:53.912
&gt;&gt; A level playing field.

00:06:53.979 --> 00:06:55.548
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: You want a level
playing field.

00:06:55.614 --> 00:06:57.115
&gt;&gt; That's all we want.

00:06:57.182 --> 00:07:00.286
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But using tariffs
to level the playing field

00:07:00.353 --> 00:07:02.121
has a flip side.

00:07:02.188 --> 00:07:03.856
They've brought unwelcome
consequences

00:07:03.923 --> 00:07:07.193
for many other U.S. businesses.

00:07:07.259 --> 00:07:09.495
I saw that not far
from Middletown.

00:07:09.562 --> 00:07:11.630
&gt;&gt; The state of Ohio could be
the hardest hit

00:07:11.697 --> 00:07:13.098
by this looming trade war

00:07:13.165 --> 00:07:15.067
with America's biggest
trading partner.

00:07:15.134 --> 00:07:16.769
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: At Industrial Tube
and Steel,

00:07:16.836 --> 00:07:20.972
Damon Gaynor is in the business
of buying and reselling steel.

00:07:21.039 --> 00:07:23.208
&gt;&gt; We buy from a bunch
of steel mills.

00:07:23.275 --> 00:07:25.678
Our main bread and butter
is distributing steel tubing.

00:07:25.744 --> 00:07:26.945
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Trump's tariffs on
imported steel--

00:07:27.012 --> 00:07:29.314
essentially a 25% tax--

00:07:29.381 --> 00:07:35.087
ended up raising the price of
American steel, too.

00:07:35.154 --> 00:07:38.791
And that sent Gaynor's costs
skyrocketing.

00:07:38.858 --> 00:07:40.359
So how did you handle that?

00:07:40.425 --> 00:07:42.728
Did you guys eat that, or did
the customers eat it?

00:07:42.795 --> 00:07:44.096 line:0%
&gt;&gt; See, that's the hard part.

00:07:44.163 --> 00:07:45.531 line:0%
We just have to pass it along
to the customer,

00:07:45.598 --> 00:07:47.800 line:0%
our customer has to pass it
along to their customer,

00:07:47.867 --> 00:07:49.668 line:0%
and so on, down the chain.

00:07:49.735 --> 00:07:51.504
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Do you think that
there'll be a point,

00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:55.208
though, where the, the end
consumer will just say,

00:07:55.274 --> 00:07:57.476
"I, I can't afford this,
this is too expensive"?

00:07:57.542 --> 00:07:59.778
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I, I think there's
always that risk,

00:07:59.845 --> 00:08:02.081
and that's the thing with
tariffs is,

00:08:02.148 --> 00:08:04.884
are you kind of artificially
messing with the price of,

00:08:04.951 --> 00:08:07.453
you know, what the market
dictates?

00:08:07.520 --> 00:08:09.021
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: And what people
will be willing to pay.

00:08:09.088 --> 00:08:10.422
&gt;&gt; And what people will be
willing to pay.

00:08:10.489 --> 00:08:12.024
Yeah, absolutely.

00:08:12.091 --> 00:08:13.593
And I think that's the question
with tariffs.

00:08:13.659 --> 00:08:17.429
Is it going to do good,
or is it going to do bad?

00:08:17.496 --> 00:08:20.298
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Manufacturers like
Shepherd Chemical were also

00:08:20.365 --> 00:08:22.034
hit hard by the tariffs,

00:08:22.101 --> 00:08:25.571
especially when China retaliated
with tariffs of its own.

00:08:25.637 --> 00:08:27.773
&gt;&gt; So all these tanks around
here produce

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:29.475
various metal carboxylates.

00:08:29.542 --> 00:08:33.279
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: C.E.O. Tom Shepherd
sells products to China,

00:08:33.346 --> 00:08:36.048
and he also imports raw
materials from China.

00:08:36.114 --> 00:08:38.450 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Our sales to China
have gone down,

00:08:38.517 --> 00:08:41.687 line:0%
and our raw materials from China
have increased in cost.

00:08:41.754 --> 00:08:43.855 line:8%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: How big of a
problem is that for you?

00:08:43.922 --> 00:08:48.660
&gt;&gt; Several million dollars of,
of profit lost, in a year.

00:08:48.727 --> 00:08:51.464
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Okay. Yeah, you're
getting it from all sides, then.

00:08:51.530 --> 00:08:53.131
&gt;&gt; Yeah, that's right.

00:08:53.198 --> 00:08:55.834
If what we're trying to do is
protect the American economy,

00:08:55.901 --> 00:08:57.803
this is a bad way to do it.

00:08:57.870 --> 00:09:00.172
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But despite the
uneven consequences,

00:09:00.238 --> 00:09:04.777
President Trump was all in
on the tariff strategy.

00:09:04.843 --> 00:09:07.679
It's a strategy he's been
talking about for years,

00:09:07.746 --> 00:09:10.649
as far back as the late 1980s,

00:09:10.716 --> 00:09:12.318
when he first tested
the possibility

00:09:12.384 --> 00:09:14.219
of becoming president.

00:09:14.286 --> 00:09:16.755 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Our guest, the famed
developer Donald Trump

00:09:16.822 --> 00:09:18.157 line:0%
of New York...

00:09:18.224 --> 00:09:20.092 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Back then, Trump's
target was Japan

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:21.694 line:0%
and its trade practices.

00:09:21.761 --> 00:09:23.395
&gt;&gt; The fact is that you don't
have free trade.

00:09:23.462 --> 00:09:25.131
We think of it as free trade,

00:09:25.197 --> 00:09:26.332
but you right now don't have
free trade.

00:09:26.399 --> 00:09:28.534
And I think lot of people are
tired

00:09:28.601 --> 00:09:30.235
of watching other countries
ripping off the United States.

00:09:30.302 --> 00:09:31.370
This is a great country.

00:09:31.436 --> 00:09:33.972
&gt;&gt; He believed from the
beginning

00:09:34.039 --> 00:09:36.975
that there's really nothing
worse than being laughed at.

00:09:37.042 --> 00:09:39.011
&gt;&gt; They laugh at us behind our
backs, they laugh at us,

00:09:39.078 --> 00:09:40.379
because of our own stupidity.

00:09:40.446 --> 00:09:43.382 line:0%
&gt;&gt; And he came to see the
Japanese as laughing

00:09:43.449 --> 00:09:46.652 line:0%
at the United States and taking
advantage of the United States

00:09:46.719 --> 00:09:50.990 line:0%
by stealing the jobs,
by dumping product here.

00:09:51.057 --> 00:09:52.724 line:0%
&gt;&gt; We let Japan come in and dump
everything right

00:09:52.791 --> 00:09:54.359 line:0%
into our markets and everything.

00:09:54.426 --> 00:09:55.894 line:0%
It's not free trade.

00:09:55.961 --> 00:09:57.997 line:0%
If you ever go to Japan right
now and try to sell something,

00:09:58.064 --> 00:09:59.832 line:0%
forget about it, Oprah, just
forget about it,

00:09:59.899 --> 00:10:01.500 line:0%
it's almost impossible.

00:10:01.567 --> 00:10:03.368
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: After Japan's
economy cratered,

00:10:03.435 --> 00:10:06.771
Trump shifted his ire to a
rising economic power, China.

00:10:06.838 --> 00:10:09.541
&gt;&gt; They are ripping us like
we've never been ripped before.

00:10:09.608 --> 00:10:12.945
If you look at Japan,
if you look at China,

00:10:13.011 --> 00:10:16.181
where we lose $100 billion
a year with China...

00:10:16.248 --> 00:10:18.417
&gt;&gt; He's been saying the same
thing for 30 years.

00:10:18.484 --> 00:10:21.253
Donald Trump has a very binary
view of life

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:22.521
and certainly of the world.

00:10:22.588 --> 00:10:25.424
And, and so to confront China,

00:10:25.491 --> 00:10:28.327
which he perceives as America's
most important

00:10:28.394 --> 00:10:32.765
and dangerous rival, and to be
able to use blunt instruments

00:10:32.832 --> 00:10:36.835
against them, and to come out
and at least be able to say

00:10:36.902 --> 00:10:38.703
that you are a winner
and they are a loser,

00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:40.906
there's, it's hard to imagine
anything more appealing

00:10:40.973 --> 00:10:42.875
to the core of his personality.

00:10:42.942 --> 00:10:47.479
&gt;&gt; Please welcome the next
president of the United States,

00:10:47.546 --> 00:10:51.283
Mr. Donald J. Trump.

00:10:51.350 --> 00:10:52.684
(people applauding and cheering)

00:10:52.751 --> 00:10:55.954
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: By 2016, Trump's
message had finally found

00:10:56.021 --> 00:10:57.889
an audience.

00:10:57.956 --> 00:11:01.661
And his focus on trade
and China had found its moment.

00:11:01.727 --> 00:11:04.763
&gt;&gt; First time I ever met Trump,
I was, you know,

00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:07.566
coming out of Goldman Sachs,
and, and being somebody

00:11:07.633 --> 00:11:09.068
that had been in finance for a
number of years,

00:11:09.135 --> 00:11:11.536
I was set to be unimpressed.

00:11:11.603 --> 00:11:14.739
I was actually very impressed.

00:11:14.806 --> 00:11:16.208 line:0%
Now, he didn't know a lot of
details.

00:11:16.275 --> 00:11:17.676 line:0%
He knew almost no policy.

00:11:17.743 --> 00:11:20.279 line:0%
But what I found most
extraordinary was,

00:11:20.346 --> 00:11:21.413 line:0%
when we got to the section on
China,

00:11:21.480 --> 00:11:22.481 line:0%
which I kind of threw out there,

00:11:22.548 --> 00:11:26.451 line:0%
of a two-hour meeting, almost 30
minutes or more

00:11:26.518 --> 00:11:27.720 line:0%
was all about China.

00:11:27.786 --> 00:11:29.754
&gt;&gt; We have a $500 billion
deficit,

00:11:29.821 --> 00:11:32.390
trade deficit with China.

00:11:32.457 --> 00:11:35.193
&gt;&gt; And you've got to remember, a
lot of this he was just reciting

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:37.863
everything he'd heard
from Lou Dobbs.

00:11:37.929 --> 00:11:40.999 line:0%
&gt;&gt; We're talking about a trade
deficit of $315 billion

00:11:41.066 --> 00:11:42.601 line:0%
last year with the Chinese.

00:11:42.667 --> 00:11:44.102 line:0%
&gt;&gt; He's been a guy that's
watched Lou Dobbs

00:11:44.169 --> 00:11:45.403 line:0%
for 30 or 40 years.

00:11:45.470 --> 00:11:48.840 line:0%
And the only thing he had formed
as a worldview was China.

00:11:48.907 --> 00:11:53.412
&gt;&gt; Because we can't continue to
allow China to rape our country,

00:11:53.479 --> 00:11:55.047
and that's what they're doing.

00:11:55.114 --> 00:11:58.884
It's the greatest theft
in the history of the world.

00:11:58.950 --> 00:12:01.787
&gt;&gt; He talked in this kind of
vernacular that,

00:12:01.853 --> 00:12:03.922
that kind of hit people
in the, in the gut,

00:12:03.989 --> 00:12:05.824
and particularly when he talked
about trade and jobs

00:12:05.891 --> 00:12:06.992
and jobs shifting overseas.

00:12:07.058 --> 00:12:08.460
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What was his
message

00:12:08.526 --> 00:12:10.829
to these people on trade?
"China's to blame"?

00:12:10.896 --> 00:12:12.597
&gt;&gt; Yeah, the message's
very simple, is that,

00:12:12.664 --> 00:12:14.366
"The elite shipped the jobs
overseas,

00:12:14.433 --> 00:12:16.268
and I'm going to bring
them back."

00:12:16.334 --> 00:12:17.969
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Indiana.

00:12:18.036 --> 00:12:20.672
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: That message helped
propel Trump to the presidency.

00:12:20.739 --> 00:12:25.778
And once there, he assembled
his team of advisers on trade.

00:12:25.845 --> 00:12:28.113
To oversee economic policy,

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:30.449
he brought in the former
president of Goldman Sachs,

00:12:30.515 --> 00:12:32.184
Gary Cohn.

00:12:32.250 --> 00:12:34.353
&gt;&gt; The job I had
in the White House

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:38.123
was to convene everyone who
basically had an opinion

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:41.927
on an economic topic,
and try and come up

00:12:41.994 --> 00:12:47.232
with a recommendation or two,
or present to the president

00:12:47.299 --> 00:12:49.602
completely diametrically opposed
opinions

00:12:49.668 --> 00:12:51.870
and allow the president
to make a decision.

00:12:51.937 --> 00:12:54.373
&gt;&gt; In the Roosevelt Room,
we would have a trade meeting

00:12:54.440 --> 00:12:56.941
every Tuesday, and then we would
take some version of that

00:12:57.008 --> 00:12:59.478
into the Oval
in a smaller group.

00:12:59.545 --> 00:13:02.380
If you take all the other
nastiness

00:13:02.447 --> 00:13:04.783
on the things like
the Paris Accord and TPP,

00:13:04.850 --> 00:13:06.685
all this other stuff,
roll it up,

00:13:06.752 --> 00:13:08.653
and put it to the factor of ten,

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:10.889
they don't compare to these
weekly nasty trade meetings.

00:13:10.956 --> 00:13:12.357
♪ ♪

00:13:12.424 --> 00:13:15.293
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: From the start, the
weekly trade meetings surfaced

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:18.664
deep divisions among Trump's
advisers over how to deal

00:13:18.731 --> 00:13:22.401
with rising economic tensions
with China.

00:13:22.468 --> 00:13:25.003
The two camps came to be known
as the globalists

00:13:25.069 --> 00:13:27.639
and the nationalists.

00:13:27.706 --> 00:13:29.774
On the one side, the globalists
included

00:13:29.841 --> 00:13:32.344
former Wall Street executives
like Gary Cohn

00:13:32.411 --> 00:13:34.513
and Steve Mnuchin.

00:13:34.579 --> 00:13:37.650
On the other side, the
nationalists included Bannon,

00:13:37.716 --> 00:13:40.986
along with Robert Lighthizer
and Peter Navarro,

00:13:41.053 --> 00:13:44.022
a hawkish economist whose film
"Death by China"

00:13:44.089 --> 00:13:45.824
caught Trump's attention.

00:13:45.890 --> 00:13:48.861
&gt;&gt; One of the most urgent
problems facing America,

00:13:48.927 --> 00:13:50.128
its increasingly destructive
trade relationship

00:13:50.195 --> 00:13:54.165
with a rapidly rising China.

00:13:54.232 --> 00:13:56.068
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The two camps
disagreed sharply

00:13:56.135 --> 00:13:59.437
over whether aggressive measures
like tariffs would help

00:13:59.504 --> 00:14:01.774
or hurt the American economy.

00:14:01.840 --> 00:14:04.976
&gt;&gt; We had a mindset that to be a
great power,

00:14:05.043 --> 00:14:06.645
you know, it wasn't just
your military.

00:14:06.712 --> 00:14:08.514
You had to be a great economic
power.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:11.016
And a great power had to be
built upon,

00:14:11.083 --> 00:14:13.084
had to be built upon
a great manufacturing base.

00:14:13.151 --> 00:14:15.587
To "make America great again,"

00:14:15.654 --> 00:14:17.122
you've got to bring
manufacturing back

00:14:17.189 --> 00:14:18.724
to the country.

00:14:18.791 --> 00:14:20.692
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Some of the people
that are very pro-tariff

00:14:20.759 --> 00:14:23.261
right now make an argument that
the United States has lost

00:14:23.328 --> 00:14:25.664
its manufacturing base,

00:14:25.731 --> 00:14:29.534
and that this is actually real
people's lives at stake here.

00:14:29.601 --> 00:14:32.237 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Well, the data would show

00:14:32.304 --> 00:14:35.374 line:0%
manufacturing jobs have gone
down in the United States,

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:37.776 line:0%
so I understand where they're
saying there.

00:14:37.842 --> 00:14:41.013
The flip side is,
factory output,

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:43.515
or what we produce in the United
States, has actually gone up.

00:14:43.582 --> 00:14:46.351
There's this thing called
technology

00:14:46.418 --> 00:14:48.787
that's happened
in the United States.

00:14:48.854 --> 00:14:50.488
Factories have changed.

00:14:50.555 --> 00:14:54.626
But we have also created
millions upon millions of jobs

00:14:54.693 --> 00:14:57.996
in new industries that didn't
exist 20 years ago.

00:14:58.063 --> 00:15:00.665
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The split between
globalists and nationalists

00:15:00.732 --> 00:15:03.802
was about more than just
industrial policy.

00:15:03.869 --> 00:15:06.271
It reflected a fundamental
difference

00:15:06.337 --> 00:15:09.708
over how best to confront China
and what each saw

00:15:09.775 --> 00:15:11.176
as the endgame.

00:15:11.243 --> 00:15:14.146
&gt;&gt; The nationalists said,
"This is a great hegemonic,

00:15:14.213 --> 00:15:16.115
you know, great-power struggle."

00:15:16.181 --> 00:15:18.817
It's definitely two systems that
couldn't be more

00:15:18.884 --> 00:15:20.352
radically different, right,

00:15:20.419 --> 00:15:22.520
and, and one of these
two are going to win.

00:15:22.587 --> 00:15:24.055
We need not just a trade deal,

00:15:24.122 --> 00:15:27.626
we need fundamental structural
changes in your economy.

00:15:27.693 --> 00:15:29.127
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Some of your former
colleagues have sat

00:15:29.194 --> 00:15:31.063
exactly where you are and said,

00:15:31.129 --> 00:15:33.231
"This is a winner-takes-all
situation."

00:15:33.298 --> 00:15:34.766
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I, I understand that,

00:15:34.833 --> 00:15:36.868
and that's the nationalist
versus the globalist.

00:15:36.935 --> 00:15:38.370
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Yeah.
&gt;&gt; The globalist, okay.

00:15:38.437 --> 00:15:42.040
As a globalist,
as a market practitioner,

00:15:42.107 --> 00:15:45.077
I think that we can have

00:15:45.143 --> 00:15:49.047
a globalized world
that works well.

00:15:49.114 --> 00:15:53.484
The question is, "Can we both be
complementary to each other?"

00:15:53.551 --> 00:15:55.587
I think the answer is yes.

00:15:55.653 --> 00:15:57.689
&gt;&gt; These arguments would get
quite personal.

00:15:57.756 --> 00:15:59.391
We would get through
the facts quickly,

00:15:59.458 --> 00:16:00.559
because the two sides are just
never going

00:16:00.626 --> 00:16:01.994
to agree what the facts are.

00:16:02.060 --> 00:16:03.629
Then it would get,
then it would get personal.

00:16:03.695 --> 00:16:05.564
&gt;&gt; From time to time, there were
people that tried

00:16:05.630 --> 00:16:08.233
to use un-footnoted,
undocumented facts.

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:10.134
It's my job to get rid of the
undocumented,

00:16:10.201 --> 00:16:13.472
un-footnoted facts, and make
sure that those don't enter

00:16:13.539 --> 00:16:15.307
the Oval Office.

00:16:15.374 --> 00:16:16.641
&gt;&gt; And a couple of times,
we had blowups.

00:16:16.708 --> 00:16:19.043
I mean, there was a blowup in
the Oval Office

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:20.579
that Kelly had to... we kind
of...

00:16:20.645 --> 00:16:22.414
the first couple of days
General Kelly was there,

00:16:22.481 --> 00:16:25.216
we had to exit and go back into
the Roosevelt Room,

00:16:25.283 --> 00:16:27.151
and it's kind of a, it's kind
of, uh, in-your-face

00:16:27.218 --> 00:16:28.620
with a couple of people.

00:16:28.687 --> 00:16:30.922
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Where was Trump
while these two parties

00:16:30.989 --> 00:16:32.624
are on different sides of this?

00:16:32.691 --> 00:16:34.726
&gt;&gt; He has a default position.

00:16:34.793 --> 00:16:36.628
His default position is,
you know, "Build the wall."

00:16:36.695 --> 00:16:37.896
His default position is,

00:16:37.963 --> 00:16:40.565
"Engage, engage China
in the economic war."

00:16:40.632 --> 00:16:42.467 line:0%
You know, "Get tariffs,"

00:16:42.534 --> 00:16:44.369 line:0%
but he's going to let you fight
it out.

00:16:44.436 --> 00:16:46.572 line:0%
&gt;&gt; President Donald Trump
arrived in China

00:16:46.638 --> 00:16:48.240 line:0%
for his first official
visit there.

00:16:48.306 --> 00:16:49.707 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: With the battle
between the two camps

00:16:49.774 --> 00:16:55.881 line:0%
playing out, Trump headed
to Beijing in November 2017.

00:16:55.948 --> 00:16:57.749
It was a royal welcoming...

00:16:57.816 --> 00:17:02.921
(band playing march)

00:17:02.987 --> 00:17:05.157
...filled with pomp and
ceremony,

00:17:05.223 --> 00:17:07.592
and the two leaders seemed ready
to work together.

00:17:07.659 --> 00:17:14.166
(band continues playing)

00:17:14.232 --> 00:17:16.334
Their negotiators agreed
on a plan for China

00:17:16.401 --> 00:17:18.636
to buy billions of dollars
in U.S. products,

00:17:18.703 --> 00:17:21.739
like beef and natural gas.

00:17:21.806 --> 00:17:24.275 line:0%
♪ ♪

00:17:24.342 --> 00:17:25.610 line:0%
But behind the celebrations,

00:17:25.677 --> 00:17:30.182 line:0%
Trump's nationalists had devised
a different plan.

00:17:30.248 --> 00:17:32.985
&gt;&gt; We had a couple of tricks up
our sleeves.

00:17:35.554 --> 00:17:39.457
Navarro and I start to dust off
the, the secret weapon we had,

00:17:39.524 --> 00:17:41.527
to call a national security
emergency,

00:17:41.593 --> 00:17:43.027
kind of what we're doing
on the border right now.

00:17:43.094 --> 00:17:45.030
(people applauding)

00:17:45.096 --> 00:17:47.465
To use the national security
emergency powers

00:17:47.532 --> 00:17:49.935
that are invested
in the Defense Department

00:17:50.001 --> 00:17:52.504
to really start to go after
steel, aluminum,

00:17:52.571 --> 00:17:55.206
maybe autos,
but eventually technology.

00:17:55.273 --> 00:17:56.975
It's time to get it on.

00:17:57.042 --> 00:18:00.045
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: By March 2018, the
president was ready

00:18:00.112 --> 00:18:02.881
to take action.

00:18:02.947 --> 00:18:05.317
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much,
everyone.

00:18:05.383 --> 00:18:08.453
We have with us the biggest
steel companies

00:18:08.519 --> 00:18:09.821
in the United States.

00:18:09.888 --> 00:18:11.756
They used to be a lot bigger,

00:18:11.823 --> 00:18:13.759
but they're going to be a lot
bigger again.

00:18:13.826 --> 00:18:16.528
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Executives from the
steel and aluminum industries

00:18:16.595 --> 00:18:19.130
were hastily gathered
in Washington.

00:18:19.197 --> 00:18:21.399 line:0%
&gt;&gt; They were all called to the
White House, had the meeting.

00:18:21.466 --> 00:18:23.768 line:0%
And at that time, the president
announced

00:18:23.835 --> 00:18:25.770 line:0%
what he was going to do.

00:18:25.837 --> 00:18:30.208
&gt;&gt; Next week, we'll be imposing
tariffs on steel imports

00:18:30.275 --> 00:18:32.110
and tariffs on aluminum imports.

00:18:32.177 --> 00:18:34.012
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What was the
reaction?

00:18:34.079 --> 00:18:36.648
&gt;&gt; The reaction was surprise.

00:18:36.715 --> 00:18:39.384
&gt;&gt; It will be 25% for steel.

00:18:39.451 --> 00:18:41.152
It will be ten percent
for aluminum.

00:18:41.219 --> 00:18:42.888
&gt;&gt; This moment was a seminal
moment in trade policy,

00:18:42.955 --> 00:18:46.325
because it's the most
aggressive use

00:18:46.391 --> 00:18:49.127
of this kind of trade law
approach ever.

00:18:49.193 --> 00:18:52.731
This is done under the theory
of national security.

00:18:52.797 --> 00:18:54.632
&gt;&gt; And we need it.
We need it even for defense.

00:18:54.699 --> 00:18:57.034
If you think, I mean,
we need itfor defense.

00:18:57.101 --> 00:18:58.469
We need great steelmakers.

00:18:58.536 --> 00:19:02.708
&gt;&gt; Steel was important to our
national security broadly.

00:19:02.774 --> 00:19:05.143
Military, critical
infrastructure,

00:19:05.210 --> 00:19:06.778
and the economy as a whole.

00:19:06.845 --> 00:19:08.747
And that had never been done
before.

00:19:08.814 --> 00:19:12.016
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much,
everybody, thank you.

00:19:12.083 --> 00:19:13.218
Thank you very much.

00:19:13.285 --> 00:19:15.153
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN:
The sweeping steel tariffs

00:19:15.220 --> 00:19:17.722
also surprised America's closest
allies.

00:19:17.789 --> 00:19:21.659
It turns out, those tariffs hurt
U.S. allies more than China.

00:19:21.726 --> 00:19:25.497
That's because allies like
Canada sell much more steel

00:19:25.564 --> 00:19:28.934
to the U.S. than China does.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.336
At the State Department,
the top China specialist

00:19:31.403 --> 00:19:34.505
quickly started getting
complaints.

00:19:34.572 --> 00:19:37.209
What were some of the United
States' allies saying?

00:19:37.275 --> 00:19:41.012 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Well, certainly the allies
were very much taken aback

00:19:41.079 --> 00:19:44.449 line:0%
that they were the target
of the steel tariffs.

00:19:44.515 --> 00:19:47.218
They don't understand the focus
on tariffs,

00:19:47.285 --> 00:19:48.820
they don't understand
the focus on deficits,

00:19:48.887 --> 00:19:50.922
they don't understand
the rejection

00:19:50.989 --> 00:19:53.825
of the international trading,

00:19:53.891 --> 00:19:55.259
you know, norms
and institutions.

00:19:55.326 --> 00:19:58.930
They don't understand the U.S.'s
rejection of global free trade,

00:19:58.996 --> 00:20:02.500
since this is the system
that we basically set up.

00:20:02.567 --> 00:20:06.305
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Trump had upended
decades of U.S. trade policy,

00:20:06.371 --> 00:20:09.708
determined to start a fight
he felt was his.

00:20:09.775 --> 00:20:12.310
&gt;&gt; In several meetings,
even in high-level meetings

00:20:12.377 --> 00:20:14.179
with the president,
some foreign leaders,

00:20:14.246 --> 00:20:16.781
you know, offered, they said,
"We want to help with China,

00:20:16.848 --> 00:20:19.617
we want to do this together
with you."

00:20:19.684 --> 00:20:22.387
But he seemed to think that this
was his fight alone

00:20:22.453 --> 00:20:26.024
and that he wanted to do it
mano a mano.

00:20:26.090 --> 00:20:29.560
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: At that point, were
you disappointed?

00:20:29.627 --> 00:20:31.396
Were you frustrated?

00:20:31.463 --> 00:20:36.601
&gt;&gt; If you adamantly believe that
something doesn't make sense,

00:20:36.668 --> 00:20:38.837
you're personally disappointed,

00:20:38.904 --> 00:20:41.506
but, ultimately, it's not your
decision to make.

00:20:41.573 --> 00:20:42.674
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Within a month,

00:20:42.740 --> 00:20:44.642
Cohn would leave
the White House.

00:20:44.709 --> 00:20:46.411
The nationalists had won.

00:20:46.478 --> 00:20:49.847 line:0%
&gt;&gt; President Trump turning tough
trade talk into action.

00:20:49.914 --> 00:20:52.383 line:0%
&gt;&gt; New tariffs announced
by the Trump administration

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:55.387 line:0%
on $50 billion worth of Chinese
exports.

00:20:55.453 --> 00:20:58.589 line:0%
&gt;&gt; China is now punching back
with an equal amount

00:20:58.656 --> 00:21:00.492 line:0%
of tariffs on American exports.

00:21:00.559 --> 00:21:02.527 line:0%
&gt;&gt; President Trump has just
slapped tariffs

00:21:02.594 --> 00:21:06.331 line:0%
on another $200 billion of
Chinese exports.

00:21:06.397 --> 00:21:10.201 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Igniting the biggest trade
war in economic history.

00:21:10.268 --> 00:21:12.503
(train bell ringing)

00:21:12.570 --> 00:21:13.872
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: This was the tariff
fight

00:21:13.938 --> 00:21:16.407
that had first brought me
to Ohio.

00:21:16.474 --> 00:21:20.478
It's what was dominating the
headlines and the politics.

00:21:20.545 --> 00:21:26.618
But the view was much different
7,000 miles away, in China.

00:21:26.685 --> 00:21:29.988
♪ ♪

