00:23:04.015 --> 00:23:05.984
As I traveled around
the country...

00:23:06.051 --> 00:23:07.852
Nihao.
&gt;&gt; Nihao.

00:23:07.919 --> 00:23:09.721
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Hello.
Some Chinese businesses told me

00:23:09.788 --> 00:23:13.791
they'd been hurt a bit,
and others not much at all.

00:23:13.858 --> 00:23:15.660
When it came to the trade war,

00:23:15.726 --> 00:23:18.930
even the government
was downplaying it.

00:23:18.997 --> 00:23:22.033
One of China's top trade
officials agreed to talk to me.

00:23:22.100 --> 00:23:24.002
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Why do you think
the U.S. and China

00:23:24.069 --> 00:23:26.805
are in a trade dispute
right now?

00:23:26.871 --> 00:23:31.343
&gt;&gt; I think we may have different
perceptions.

00:23:31.409 --> 00:23:38.817 line:0%
We think that the Pacific Ocean
as, in President Xi's words,

00:23:38.884 --> 00:23:45.790 line:0%
"Big enough to accommodate
the two economies."

00:23:45.857 --> 00:23:51.696
We do not want to have a war,
even a trade war,

00:23:51.763 --> 00:23:54.599
with any country in the world.

00:23:54.666 --> 00:24:00.705
And we do not have
the secret strategy

00:24:00.772 --> 00:24:05.977
to replace the United States
as the global superpower.

00:24:06.044 --> 00:24:07.879
♪ ♪

00:24:07.946 --> 00:24:10.015
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But U.S. companies
have long complained

00:24:10.081 --> 00:24:13.518
about an economic strategy
that China does use.

00:24:13.585 --> 00:24:18.389
They say it gives Chinese
businesses an unfair advantage.

00:24:18.456 --> 00:24:21.426
The government plays a heavy
hand in the market here,

00:24:21.493 --> 00:24:25.796
through massive subsidies
and support.

00:24:25.863 --> 00:24:28.533
Special economic zones,
for example, have been created

00:24:28.600 --> 00:24:30.702
to spur industries the
government believes

00:24:30.769 --> 00:24:34.506
are critical to China's success.

00:24:34.572 --> 00:24:37.209
I found one six hours south of
Shanghai,

00:24:37.275 --> 00:24:40.712
in the industrial port city
of Wenzhou.

00:24:40.778 --> 00:24:45.650
This economic strategy is called
"The China Model."

00:24:45.717 --> 00:24:49.220
&gt;&gt; The China Model is a blend
between national control

00:24:49.287 --> 00:24:52.556
and ownership of resources and
economic activities dominated

00:24:52.623 --> 00:24:54.992
by private entrepreneurs.

00:24:55.059 --> 00:24:56.928 line:0%
90% of the new jobs are
in the private sector,

00:24:56.995 --> 00:25:01.532 line:0%
but all the land is still owned
by the state.

00:25:01.599 --> 00:25:04.869 line:0%
Control of energy resources
controlled by the state.

00:25:04.936 --> 00:25:08.239
Control of the financial system,
basically by the state.

00:25:08.306 --> 00:25:10.041
So you come up
with this socialism

00:25:10.108 --> 00:25:13.378
with Chinese characteristics,
or socialist market economy,

00:25:13.444 --> 00:25:16.247
which is what China calls
itself.

00:25:16.314 --> 00:25:19.184
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Here in Wenzhou,
the government has prioritized

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:22.019
high-tech development,
providing support to companies

00:25:22.086 --> 00:25:27.124
like WM Motor
to build electric cars.

00:25:27.191 --> 00:25:31.529
In 16 months, WM built
a massive manufacturing facility

00:25:31.596 --> 00:25:35.132
that will be able to produce
200,000 electric cars a year.

00:25:35.199 --> 00:25:38.904
(music playing in commercial)

00:25:38.970 --> 00:25:41.906
&gt;&gt; We focus on
the intelligent smart car.

00:25:41.973 --> 00:25:43.541
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: And this is them?
These are the cars?

00:25:43.608 --> 00:25:46.745
&gt;&gt; Yes, this is actually
the very early-stage car...

00:25:46.811 --> 00:25:50.348
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Freeman Shen
is the C.E.O. of WM Motor.

00:25:50.415 --> 00:25:53.484
♪ ♪

00:25:53.551 --> 00:25:57.655
The China market for auto sales
is now the biggest in the world.

00:25:57.722 --> 00:25:59.991
It's also where American car
companies make

00:26:00.058 --> 00:26:04.162
some of their biggest profits.

00:26:04.229 --> 00:26:06.331
But they're facing increasing
competition

00:26:06.398 --> 00:26:10.135
from Chinese companies, like WM.

00:26:10.201 --> 00:26:14.305
How does this represent sort of
a changing China?

00:26:14.372 --> 00:26:15.406
&gt;&gt; Oh, interesting.

00:26:15.473 --> 00:26:18.109 line:0%
You know, when a
country upgrading

00:26:18.176 --> 00:26:19.978 line:0%
the whole industrial base,

00:26:20.044 --> 00:26:24.048 line:0%
the best example would be a,
a vehicle, the car industry.

00:26:24.115 --> 00:26:25.516
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Car industry.

00:26:25.583 --> 00:26:26.718
&gt;&gt; Yeah, car industry
is the representative

00:26:26.784 --> 00:26:28.186
of the whole industry.

00:26:28.253 --> 00:26:30.588
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: You're saying,
like, the, the cars are

00:26:30.655 --> 00:26:32.590
the, the bellwether of
how a country...

00:26:32.657 --> 00:26:34.024
&gt;&gt; Exactly, exactly-- exactly.

00:26:34.091 --> 00:26:35.527
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Why, why do cars...
&gt;&gt; Because, you know,

00:26:35.593 --> 00:26:37.895
it's assembly of all kind of
technology.

00:26:37.962 --> 00:26:42.500
It's equally software,
mechanical, lighting.

00:26:42.567 --> 00:26:46.203
You've got,
cybersecurity's in there.

00:26:46.270 --> 00:26:47.271
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: So you're saying
that countries

00:26:47.338 --> 00:26:49.374
that can build a car...

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:50.808
&gt;&gt; You've got all kind of
industry very strong

00:26:50.875 --> 00:26:52.811
before you can build a strong
car in that country.

00:26:52.877 --> 00:26:54.178
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: And if you can
build a car,

00:26:54.245 --> 00:26:56.814
it means you are moving up
the technology chain.

00:26:56.881 --> 00:26:58.582
&gt;&gt; Exactly, exactly.
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: You're coming up.

00:26:58.649 --> 00:27:00.385
&gt;&gt; The value chain, basically.
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The value chain.

00:27:00.452 --> 00:27:01.686
&gt;&gt; Is going up.

00:27:01.753 --> 00:27:02.954
&gt;&gt; Well, the Communist Party
has long seen

00:27:03.021 --> 00:27:05.690
the automotive industry
as a pillar industry.

00:27:05.757 --> 00:27:07.525
And so they've devoted huge
amounts of resources

00:27:07.592 --> 00:27:11.096
and policies towards building up
that industry.

00:27:11.162 --> 00:27:14.765 line:0%
It's all about bringing China
up into the top tier

00:27:14.832 --> 00:27:18.235 line:0%
of global economies, in terms of
its manufacturing capabilities

00:27:18.302 --> 00:27:20.037 line:0%
and technological capabilities.

00:27:20.104 --> 00:27:21.372
You're not going to get rich,

00:27:21.439 --> 00:27:22.841
you're not going to become
a superpower

00:27:22.907 --> 00:27:24.842
if you're just making
the low-end stuff.

00:27:24.909 --> 00:27:27.178
♪ ♪

00:27:27.245 --> 00:27:29.847
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The state-sponsored
China Model is credited

00:27:29.914 --> 00:27:33.617
with transforming the country's
economy.

00:27:33.684 --> 00:27:35.486
China's middle class is now
bigger

00:27:35.553 --> 00:27:38.623
than the entire United States.

00:27:38.690 --> 00:27:44.062
And its economy is growing twice
as fast.

00:27:44.128 --> 00:27:46.430
This success has become a major
source of tension

00:27:46.497 --> 00:27:48.766
in the trade war.

00:27:48.833 --> 00:27:51.936 line:0%
&gt;&gt; The question is,
is America complaining

00:27:52.003 --> 00:27:56.107 line:0%
about the way China handles
economy,

00:27:56.174 --> 00:28:01.011 line:0%
or is about China's legitimacy
to become a prosperous

00:28:01.078 --> 00:28:02.914 line:0%
and powerful country?

00:28:02.981 --> 00:28:06.216
Our population is four times
bigger than the U.S.

00:28:06.283 --> 00:28:09.320
We have 1.3 billion people.
Right?

00:28:09.387 --> 00:28:11.222
You have 300 million people.

00:28:11.288 --> 00:28:14.459
So China's economy should be
four times higher

00:28:14.525 --> 00:28:17.128
than the U.S. economy.
Now we are only...

00:28:17.194 --> 00:28:18.562
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: That would be
difficult for people

00:28:18.629 --> 00:28:20.464
in the United States to accept.
&gt;&gt; Yeah, of course, I know,

00:28:20.531 --> 00:28:25.169
this is, this is difficult to,
to accept, right?

00:28:25.236 --> 00:28:29.707
Today we are only 60%
of the size of the U.S.

00:28:29.774 --> 00:28:35.780
I think we do have the right
to be at least as powerful

00:28:35.847 --> 00:28:40.551
as the U.S. and even, one day,
much powerful than the U.S.

00:28:40.618 --> 00:28:44.288
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Do you think that
Americans should be worried?

00:28:44.355 --> 00:28:46.825
&gt;&gt; Oh, yes, I think so.
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Yes, they should?

00:28:46.891 --> 00:28:49.394
&gt;&gt; You know, the Chinese
government thinking

00:28:49.461 --> 00:28:52.163
we are become stronger
and stronger.

00:28:52.229 --> 00:28:54.098
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Yeah.
&gt;&gt; And the U.S. still

00:28:54.165 --> 00:28:57.068
number one, big brother, right?
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Big brother.

00:28:57.135 --> 00:29:01.439
&gt;&gt; And hope that big brother not
trying to punch me on my face.

00:29:01.505 --> 00:29:03.241
And big brother were thinking,
you know,

00:29:03.307 --> 00:29:05.076
"This little brother someday
probably will do

00:29:05.143 --> 00:29:06.677
something to me."

00:29:06.744 --> 00:29:08.813
I think that the... it is...

00:29:08.879 --> 00:29:11.483
I think that really depends on
the, the intelligence

00:29:11.549 --> 00:29:14.351
of both countries' leader
to make sure.

00:29:14.418 --> 00:29:16.087
Worry is fine.
But please don't fight.

00:29:16.154 --> 00:29:17.588
♪ ♪

00:29:17.655 --> 00:29:21.259 line:0%
(audience applauding)

00:29:21.325 --> 00:29:23.160 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But back
in the U.S.,

00:29:23.227 --> 00:29:25.329 line:0%
Trump was eager to escalate the
tariff fight.

00:29:25.396 --> 00:29:26.764 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much.

00:29:26.831 --> 00:29:29.667 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: In fall of 2018,
he upped the ante

00:29:29.734 --> 00:29:32.103 line:0%
by threatening even more
tariffs.

00:29:32.170 --> 00:29:37.808
&gt;&gt; As you know, we have $250
billion at 25% interest

00:29:37.875 --> 00:29:43.514
with China right now, and we
could go $267 billion more.

00:29:43.581 --> 00:29:46.250
And China wants to talk
very badly.

00:29:46.317 --> 00:29:48.385
And I said, "Frankly,
it's too early to talk."

00:29:48.452 --> 00:29:50.588
Can't talk now,
because they're not ready.

00:29:50.654 --> 00:29:52.790
Because they've been ripping us
for so many years.

00:29:52.857 --> 00:29:54.459
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Trump's position
was that it was time

00:29:54.525 --> 00:29:57.495
to hit back, and that prior
administrations

00:29:57.562 --> 00:29:59.430
had been too soft on China.

00:29:59.496 --> 00:30:04.101
&gt;&gt; They have a surplus of
$375 billion-- with a B--

00:30:04.168 --> 00:30:05.670
with the United States,

00:30:05.736 --> 00:30:07.572
and it's been that way for
years and years and years.

00:30:07.638 --> 00:30:10.607
I don't blame China,
I blame our leadership.

00:30:10.674 --> 00:30:12.844
They should have never
let that happen.

00:30:12.910 --> 00:30:14.879
And I told that
to President Xi...

00:30:14.946 --> 00:30:17.248
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But while Trump was
blaming his predecessors,

00:30:17.315 --> 00:30:19.450
we were hearing about
other reasons

00:30:19.517 --> 00:30:22.486
why the problems with China
had gone on so long.

00:30:22.553 --> 00:30:25.356
Dozens of interviews we did
in China and the U.S.

00:30:25.423 --> 00:30:28.292
pointed to an unlikely
obstacle--

00:30:28.359 --> 00:30:30.294
American businesses themselves.

00:30:30.361 --> 00:30:33.798
&gt;&gt; They were worried about the
operations they had in China,

00:30:33.865 --> 00:30:36.400
whether they would lose
the profitability.

00:30:36.467 --> 00:30:38.803
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: One of the biggest
problems the U.S. has had

00:30:38.869 --> 00:30:41.472
with China over the years
is what's come to be known

00:30:41.539 --> 00:30:43.941
as forced tech transfer,

00:30:44.008 --> 00:30:46.377
where companies wanting to do
business in China

00:30:46.443 --> 00:30:49.513
say they're pressured to give up
their technology.

00:30:49.580 --> 00:30:52.416 line:0%
&gt;&gt; China started adopting what
were called

00:30:52.483 --> 00:30:55.886 line:0%
indigenous innovation policies
to make sure

00:30:55.953 --> 00:31:00.191 line:0%
that their own companies,
state-owned or otherwise,

00:31:00.258 --> 00:31:01.592 line:0%
were going to be the ones

00:31:01.659 --> 00:31:04.128 line:0%
who really were the leaders
in the new economy.

00:31:04.195 --> 00:31:06.563
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: So you're saying
they didn't compete fair.

00:31:06.630 --> 00:31:10.634
&gt;&gt; They engaged in predatory
and protectionist policies.

00:31:10.701 --> 00:31:13.371
They demanded that many
foreign companies

00:31:13.437 --> 00:31:16.206
seeking to come into their
market had to do it

00:31:16.273 --> 00:31:19.376
through joint ventures
with their own firms.

00:31:19.443 --> 00:31:22.580
And in many cases, requiring
that their technology

00:31:22.647 --> 00:31:27.785
be transferred to empower
Chinese entities to become,

00:31:27.852 --> 00:31:30.421
you know, great world companies.

00:31:30.487 --> 00:31:32.823
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: China wasn't
supposed to be doing this

00:31:32.890 --> 00:31:35.860
under rules set by
the World Trade Organization,

00:31:35.927 --> 00:31:38.229
which it had joined in 2001.

00:31:38.295 --> 00:31:40.932
And though China says it
has no official policies

00:31:40.999 --> 00:31:43.601
forcing companies to hand over
technology,

00:31:43.667 --> 00:31:46.103
U.S. trade officials started
getting complaints

00:31:46.170 --> 00:31:50.240
about the practice just years
after China joined the WTO.

00:31:50.307 --> 00:31:53.378
But the complaints came
with a catch.

00:31:53.444 --> 00:31:54.979
&gt;&gt; Companies would come in
and complain.

00:31:55.045 --> 00:31:56.947 line:0%
They'd have great information,
but,

00:31:57.014 --> 00:31:59.316 line:0%
"Oh, by the way, you can't use
any of this,

00:31:59.383 --> 00:32:01.419 line:0%
but solve our problem."

00:32:01.485 --> 00:32:03.721 line:0%
And so that was always
a challenge.

00:32:03.788 --> 00:32:05.422 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Why did that make
it harder?

00:32:05.489 --> 00:32:06.891
&gt;&gt; It made it harder

00:32:06.957 --> 00:32:09.026
because you couldn't really
prove your case.

00:32:09.093 --> 00:32:11.863
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: So you saw the U.S.
business community not only say,

00:32:11.929 --> 00:32:14.365 line:0%
"Don't use my name," but
they would say to your office

00:32:14.432 --> 00:32:16.767 line:0%
and the administration,

00:32:16.834 --> 00:32:18.702
"We don't even want you raising
this issue too loudly."

00:32:18.769 --> 00:32:20.237 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Right, right, right.

00:32:20.304 --> 00:32:21.539
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: "Because if you
raise this too loudly ..."

00:32:21.605 --> 00:32:22.840
&gt;&gt; "They're going to think
it's us,

00:32:22.906 --> 00:32:24.675
and we will be hurt."

00:32:24.742 --> 00:32:26.377
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: And they had too
much money at stake.

00:32:26.444 --> 00:32:27.878
&gt;&gt; They had a lot of money at
stake.

00:32:27.945 --> 00:32:29.947
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: How did that...
sort of having your hands tied

00:32:30.014 --> 00:32:32.516
behind your back in a way, how
did that affect,

00:32:32.583 --> 00:32:35.786
in the long run, the, the U.S.
position against China?

00:32:35.853 --> 00:32:38.722
&gt;&gt; Yeah, it probably emboldened
China a bit, right?

00:32:38.789 --> 00:32:41.592
Because as more and more
problems came up,

00:32:41.659 --> 00:32:44.061
individual companies
were very spooked

00:32:44.127 --> 00:32:48.632
and didn't want to, you know,
visibly be associated

00:32:48.699 --> 00:32:51.602
with any strong action
by the U.S. government.

00:32:51.669 --> 00:32:55.139
♪ ♪

00:32:55.206 --> 00:32:57.642
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: By 2008, U.S.
companies were facing

00:32:57.708 --> 00:33:00.745
more and more competition
from Chinese companies,

00:33:00.811 --> 00:33:04.848
and China was becoming
an economic force.

00:33:04.915 --> 00:33:08.018
&gt;&gt; The Chinese tonight reaching
their hands out to the world

00:33:08.085 --> 00:33:09.821
in a really unprecedented way.

00:33:09.887 --> 00:33:11.855
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The China Model
was working,

00:33:11.922 --> 00:33:14.225
and ready for prime time.

00:33:14.292 --> 00:33:16.927
That opening ceremony,
do you remember it?

00:33:16.994 --> 00:33:18.762
&gt;&gt; I was there.
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What did you see?

00:33:18.829 --> 00:33:20.564
&gt;&gt; Oh, my God.

00:33:20.631 --> 00:33:22.967
I sat up in a high seat,

00:33:23.034 --> 00:33:25.069
and I was around all these
Chinese people who'd come in

00:33:25.135 --> 00:33:28.039
from all over the country.
&gt;&gt; (cheering)

00:33:28.106 --> 00:33:29.640
&gt;&gt; They were beaming with pride.

00:33:29.706 --> 00:33:31.476 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What do you think
the world saw?

00:33:31.542 --> 00:33:33.343 line:0%
&gt;&gt; The world saw a pretty
incredible place.

00:33:33.410 --> 00:33:35.179 line:0%
I think it blew the world away.

00:33:35.245 --> 00:33:37.515 line:0%
On... "Holy cow."

00:33:37.582 --> 00:33:38.850 line:0%
And all of a sudden,

00:33:38.916 --> 00:33:42.186
they just do this incredible
opening ceremony.

00:33:42.253 --> 00:33:43.287
(crowd cheers)

00:33:43.354 --> 00:33:45.389
They know how to put on a show.

00:33:45.456 --> 00:33:48.759
It was like the biggest
coming-out party in history.

00:33:48.826 --> 00:33:54.431
&gt;&gt; (cheering)

00:33:54.498 --> 00:33:56.133
&gt;&gt; It was go-go years
in Beijing.

00:33:56.200 --> 00:33:57.734
Everything was possible.

00:33:57.801 --> 00:34:01.405 line:0%
You know, and there was still
a lot of respect for the U.S.

00:34:01.471 --> 00:34:03.407 line:0%
and the U.S. economic system,
the U.S. financial system.

00:34:03.474 --> 00:34:05.709 line:0%
And, you know, there was still
a lot of respect

00:34:05.776 --> 00:34:09.313 line:0%
for the big banks,
and the idea that the U.S....

00:34:09.380 --> 00:34:11.749 line:0%
they understood how to run a
financial market.

00:34:11.816 --> 00:34:14.217
And then... the crash happens.

00:34:14.284 --> 00:34:16.020 line:0%
(closing bell ringing)

00:34:16.087 --> 00:34:18.856 line:0%
&gt;&gt; A meltdown on Wall Street,
the worst since 9/11.

00:34:18.923 --> 00:34:21.858 line:0%
&gt;&gt; The worst financial crisis
in modern times.

00:34:21.925 --> 00:34:25.229 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Three of the five biggest
investment banks are gone.

00:34:25.296 --> 00:34:27.664 line:0%
&gt;&gt; You can see it in some
of the policy circles

00:34:27.731 --> 00:34:28.865
and the, sort of
the academic writings,

00:34:28.932 --> 00:34:31.235
the Chinese think tanks,

00:34:31.302 --> 00:34:34.238
but I just saw that with my
friends was this idea of,

00:34:34.305 --> 00:34:37.040
like, "We thought you guys knew
what you were doing."

00:34:37.107 --> 00:34:40.744
&gt;&gt; A crisis which is unraveling
homeownership, the middle class,

00:34:40.811 --> 00:34:43.948
and the American Dream itself.

00:34:44.015 --> 00:34:47.752
&gt;&gt; I definitely look at the,
the financial crisis, 2007,
2008,

00:34:47.819 --> 00:34:49.954
as a, as a really key
turning point

00:34:50.021 --> 00:34:54.758
in how the leading Chinese
thinkers saw the U.S.,

00:34:54.825 --> 00:34:57.627
where the U.S. maybe was up here
in terms of something

00:34:57.694 --> 00:35:01.398
to emulate in certain ways,
went down to here or lower,

00:35:01.465 --> 00:35:04.435
because basically the emperor
has no clothes.

00:35:04.502 --> 00:35:06.603
&gt;&gt; The attitude changed
profoundly.

00:35:06.670 --> 00:35:11.175
C.E.Os. who used to be able to
go see the, the premier,

00:35:11.242 --> 00:35:13.410
and president, they would come,

00:35:13.477 --> 00:35:14.745
and they would have to meet
a low-level official,

00:35:14.811 --> 00:35:16.814
who would berate them.

00:35:16.881 --> 00:35:17.914
It was very stark.

00:35:17.981 --> 00:35:19.950
But you got to remember,

00:35:20.017 --> 00:35:22.386
for, for all these years,
we had, you know,

00:35:22.453 --> 00:35:26.189
we had low-voltage congressmen
or businesspeople coming in

00:35:26.256 --> 00:35:29.326
and, and shaking their finger
in Chinese, saying,

00:35:29.393 --> 00:35:31.796
"You should have all the
children you want,

00:35:31.862 --> 00:35:33.597
you should do this,
you should do that."

00:35:33.664 --> 00:35:35.800
And these very capable
Chinese people

00:35:35.866 --> 00:35:38.035
would just bite their tongue
and say, you know,

00:35:38.102 --> 00:35:39.703
kind of, "Thank you
for your wisdom,"

00:35:39.770 --> 00:35:43.007
because they, they needed, they
needed America, they needed,

00:35:43.073 --> 00:35:45.843
they needed us,
so they had to tolerate us.

00:35:45.910 --> 00:35:48.245
Then all of a sudden,
global financial crisis,

00:35:48.312 --> 00:35:49.880
and it was payback time.

00:35:49.946 --> 00:35:52.950
It was, like, "You listen
to us for a while."

00:35:53.016 --> 00:35:54.552 line:0%
(crowd applauding)

00:35:54.618 --> 00:35:56.387 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Publicly, China
would promise to open

00:35:56.454 --> 00:35:58.955 line:0%
its markets more
to U.S. business.

00:35:59.022 --> 00:36:00.858 line:0%
&gt;&gt; The new Chinese leader
is revealed.

00:36:00.925 --> 00:36:03.060 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But internally, it
would double down

00:36:03.127 --> 00:36:04.895 line:0%
on the China Model.

00:36:04.962 --> 00:36:06.230 line:0%
&gt;&gt; (speaking Chinese)

00:36:06.296 --> 00:36:09.032 line:0%
(translated): China needs to
learn more about the world.

00:36:09.099 --> 00:36:11.802 line:0%
The world also needs to learn
more about China.

00:36:11.868 --> 00:36:13.003 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN:
And under Xi Jinping,

00:36:13.070 --> 00:36:16.273
it embraced an ambitious
national plan,

00:36:16.340 --> 00:36:20.677
called "Made in China 2025,"
that put even more focus

00:36:20.744 --> 00:36:24.448
on dominating key global
industries.

00:36:24.515 --> 00:36:27.752
&gt;&gt; There is this belief that
China is destined to return

00:36:27.818 --> 00:36:29.620
to its former glories,

00:36:29.686 --> 00:36:33.524
and you can't restore your,
your fabled glory

00:36:33.590 --> 00:36:35.859
if you're not the leading
country

00:36:35.926 --> 00:36:39.463
in all sorts of areas, be it
military, be it technology,

00:36:39.530 --> 00:36:41.599
be it, be it manufacturing.

00:36:41.666 --> 00:36:43.633
♪ ♪

00:36:43.700 --> 00:36:46.437
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: But early on, U.S.
businesses discovered China

00:36:46.503 --> 00:36:49.974
was also using other means
to get ahead.

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:54.444 line:0%
&gt;&gt; In early January of 2010, I
get a call from Google,

00:36:54.511 --> 00:36:56.948 line:0%
who had just announced
that they had been hacked.

00:36:57.014 --> 00:36:59.283 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Google traced the sabotage
back to China.

00:36:59.349 --> 00:37:00.784 line:0%
&gt;&gt; In the course of the
investigation,

00:37:00.851 --> 00:37:02.686 line:0%
they actually realized that
there were many more companies

00:37:02.753 --> 00:37:04.054 line:0%
that had been targeted.

00:37:04.121 --> 00:37:07.191 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Not only was Google itself
targeted by the cyber-spies,

00:37:07.257 --> 00:37:10.727 line:0%
but so were at least 20 other
major corporations.

00:37:10.794 --> 00:37:12.329
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN:
You thought at that time,

00:37:12.396 --> 00:37:13.831
"This is something bigger."

00:37:13.898 --> 00:37:17.401
&gt;&gt; For the first time ever,
we were facing a nation-state,

00:37:17.468 --> 00:37:20.470
an intelligence service, that
was breaking into companies,

00:37:20.537 --> 00:37:24.675
not governments, not militaries,
but private-sector organization.

00:37:24.742 --> 00:37:27.745 line:0%
&gt;&gt; In all more than 72
organizations were hacked

00:37:27.812 --> 00:37:30.214 line:0%
by spies, dating back to 2006.

00:37:30.280 --> 00:37:32.950 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The Google hack led
to revelations about dozens

00:37:33.017 --> 00:37:34.684 line:0%
of other Chinese cyberattacks.

00:37:34.751 --> 00:37:36.687 line:0%
&gt;&gt; ...dubbed Operation
Shady Rat.

00:37:36.754 --> 00:37:38.989 line:0%
Is it coming from one
particular place?

00:37:39.056 --> 00:37:40.491 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN:
And Alperovitch was called

00:37:40.558 --> 00:37:42.360
to the White House Situation
Room to brief

00:37:42.426 --> 00:37:45.329
Obama's top national security
officials.

00:37:45.396 --> 00:37:47.531
&gt;&gt; I briefed them on what we
were seeing with both Aurora,

00:37:47.598 --> 00:37:49.533
Night Dragon, Shady Rat.

00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:51.502
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What did they say?

00:37:51.568 --> 00:37:53.770
&gt;&gt; My impression was none
of this was a surprise.

00:37:53.837 --> 00:37:56.540
And when I pressed them on why
they were not taking

00:37:56.607 --> 00:38:00.677
stronger action against China,
their response was,

00:38:00.744 --> 00:38:03.247
"It's complicated."
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: "It's complicated."

00:38:03.313 --> 00:38:04.981
Did they explain that?

00:38:05.048 --> 00:38:06.483
&gt;&gt; Well, they were telling me
straight out,

00:38:06.550 --> 00:38:10.588
"Those same customers that are
getting victimized by China,

00:38:10.655 --> 00:38:12.722
they are the same companies
that are coming in to tell us,

00:38:12.789 --> 00:38:14.958
'Don't do anything to harm the
relationship with China.

00:38:15.025 --> 00:38:16.460
We want to continue doing
business there.

00:38:16.526 --> 00:38:18.229
We want to continue
making money there.

00:38:18.295 --> 00:38:19.630
We need that market.'"

00:38:21.298 --> 00:38:25.202 line:0%
&gt;&gt; You know, the, the U.S.
government listens to companies,

00:38:25.269 --> 00:38:29.372 line:0%
so if the companies are saying,
"Chill," they'll chill.

00:38:29.439 --> 00:38:33.510
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: How can businesses
walk into United States agencies

00:38:33.577 --> 00:38:37.380
and complain about being treated
unfairly,

00:38:37.447 --> 00:38:40.417
if they're the ones that are
preventing any action

00:38:40.484 --> 00:38:41.785
from being taken?

00:38:41.852 --> 00:38:43.654
How do they get to have it
both ways?

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:46.357
&gt;&gt; Sometimes two things can be
true at the same time.

00:38:46.423 --> 00:38:48.925
I mean, their incentives are to
make money.

00:38:48.992 --> 00:38:51.161
If your business is in China,

00:38:51.228 --> 00:38:53.430
Xi Jinping is more important
to you than Donald Trump

00:38:53.497 --> 00:38:55.232
or Barack Obama.

00:38:55.299 --> 00:38:58.068
And it's, it's not that these
are bad people

00:38:58.135 --> 00:38:59.703
who don't care about America,

00:38:59.770 --> 00:39:02.572
but their incentives are
to shareholders,

00:39:02.639 --> 00:39:05.108
not to the government
of the United States.

00:39:05.175 --> 00:39:08.812
(band playing
"Hail to the Chief")

00:39:08.879 --> 00:39:11.415
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Neither Google nor
any of the other companies

00:39:11.482 --> 00:39:15.185
we contacted about cyberattacks
would agree to talk to us.

00:39:15.252 --> 00:39:17.087
And Chinese officials deny
they've been involved

00:39:17.154 --> 00:39:19.456
in such practices.

00:39:19.523 --> 00:39:23.893
But by 2015, American businesses
and government officials

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:26.363
were increasingly alarmed.

00:39:26.430 --> 00:39:28.665
In negotiations
with President Obama,

00:39:28.732 --> 00:39:30.767
Xi pledged that China
would not engage

00:39:30.834 --> 00:39:32.636
in economic cyber-hacking.

00:39:32.703 --> 00:39:37.141
&gt;&gt; I believe that we have made
significant progress

00:39:37.207 --> 00:39:39.943
in enhancing understanding
between our two nations.

00:39:40.010 --> 00:39:42.479
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Obama also brokered
a major trade agreement

00:39:42.546 --> 00:39:46.283
with allies, the Trans-Pacific
Partnership, or TPP.

00:39:46.350 --> 00:39:49.353
(crowd applauding)

00:39:49.420 --> 00:39:51.655
It was supposed to put pressure
on China

00:39:51.722 --> 00:39:53.757
to fix the growing
economic problems

00:39:53.824 --> 00:39:56.894
between the two countries.

00:39:56.961 --> 00:39:58.729
But all of that would come
unraveled

00:39:58.795 --> 00:40:03.967
with a new president
in the White House.

00:40:04.034 --> 00:40:06.637
(march playing)

00:40:06.704 --> 00:40:10.040
Trump quickly withdrew
from the TPP agreement.

00:40:10.107 --> 00:40:11.041
And by the fall of 2018,

00:40:11.108 --> 00:40:14.878
with his own trade negotiations
stymied,

00:40:14.945 --> 00:40:16.913
the conflict was widening.

00:40:16.980 --> 00:40:20.250
The administration took
a tough turn,

00:40:20.317 --> 00:40:21.718
confronting China aggressively.

00:40:21.785 --> 00:40:24.254 line:0%
&gt;&gt; ...releasing a new report
tonight detailing

00:40:24.321 --> 00:40:26.523 line:0%
just how big the threat
China poses.

00:40:26.589 --> 00:40:29.259 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: It accused China of
breaking the cyber agreement...

00:40:29.326 --> 00:40:30.994 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Chinese intel officers
charged

00:40:31.061 --> 00:40:32.463 line:0%
with hacking U.S. businesses...

00:40:32.529 --> 00:40:35.032 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: ...and engaging in
widespread technology theft.

00:40:35.099 --> 00:40:37.801 line:0%
&gt;&gt; This latest indictment adds
to the growing tension

00:40:37.868 --> 00:40:39.669 line:0%
between the U.S. and China
in the middle

00:40:39.736 --> 00:40:41.305 line:0%
of this fierce trade war...

00:40:41.372 --> 00:40:44.174 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Now, through the
Made in China 2025 plan,

00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:46.577 line:0%
the Communist Party has set its
sights on controlling

00:40:46.644 --> 00:40:50.514 line:0%
90% of the world's most
advanced industries,

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:53.049 line:0%
including robotics,
biotechnology,

00:40:53.116 --> 00:40:54.918 line:0%
and artificial intelligence.

00:40:54.985 --> 00:40:56.820 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Really an extraordinary
speech, attacking China

00:40:56.887 --> 00:40:59.256 line:0%
on the domestic politics front,
the trade front,

00:40:59.323 --> 00:41:01.058 line:0%
and the military front.

00:41:01.125 --> 00:41:02.926 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Chinese security agencies
have masterminded

00:41:02.993 --> 00:41:05.095 line:0%
the wholesale theft
of American technology.

00:41:05.161 --> 00:41:08.098 line:0%
&gt;&gt; They don't want to wait 20
more years to catch up.

00:41:08.165 --> 00:41:09.099 line:0%
They're just reaching into the
cookie jar

00:41:09.166 --> 00:41:10.233 line:0%
and taking whatever they want...

00:41:10.300 --> 00:41:12.769 line:0%
&gt;&gt; And using that stolen
technology,

00:41:12.836 --> 00:41:16.240 line:0%
the Chinese Communist Party is
turning plowshares into swords.

00:41:16.307 --> 00:41:18.508 line:0%
&gt;&gt; That speech was not
a hawkish speech,

00:41:18.575 --> 00:41:20.944 line:0%
that speech was a declaration
of economic war

00:41:21.011 --> 00:41:22.946 line:0%
and potentially a real war.

00:41:23.013 --> 00:41:24.614 line:0%
&gt;&gt; In China, it was read
by everybody

00:41:24.681 --> 00:41:26.116 line:7%
all the way up to the top.

00:41:26.182 --> 00:41:29.887 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Did the vice president issue
any kind of evidence?

00:41:29.953 --> 00:41:33.023 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: As what?
&gt;&gt; As a harbinger of, you know,

00:41:33.090 --> 00:41:36.293 line:0%
something really,
really different

00:41:36.360 --> 00:41:39.396 line:0%
and something that was really
alarming for them.

00:41:39.463 --> 00:41:41.865 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Why was it alarming
for them?

00:41:41.932 --> 00:41:47.337 line:0%
&gt;&gt; It was a very unnuanced,
undiplomatic speech.

00:41:47.404 --> 00:41:50.373 line:0%
It was kind of a bill of
indictment.

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:53.310 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Both China and the United
States need to make an effort

00:41:53.377 --> 00:41:55.979 line:0%
to make sure
that the bilateral relations

00:41:56.046 --> 00:41:57.781 line:0%
do not get out of control.

00:41:57.848 --> 00:42:00.150 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Our message to China's rulers
is this:

00:42:00.216 --> 00:42:01.952 line:0%
This president will not back
down.

00:42:02.019 --> 00:42:03.220 line:0%
(audience applauds)

00:42:03.287 --> 00:42:05.489
&gt;&gt; That was the point
of no return,

00:42:05.556 --> 00:42:06.890
and it's not being
acknowledged enough.

00:42:06.957 --> 00:42:08.258
It was the most important speech

00:42:08.324 --> 00:42:10.193
of the whole Trump
administration.

00:42:10.260 --> 00:42:12.062 line:0%
♪ ♪

00:42:12.129 --> 00:42:14.064 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Early on, the focus
of the trade war

00:42:14.131 --> 00:42:18.968 line:0%
had been on tariffs and reviving
20th-century industries.

00:42:19.035 --> 00:42:21.938 line:0%
But it'd now become
about far more.

00:42:22.005 --> 00:42:24.407
About who will dominate
the cutting-edge industries

00:42:24.474 --> 00:42:27.477
of the 21st century.

00:42:27.544 --> 00:42:29.479
So I headed to Silicon Valley,

00:42:29.546 --> 00:42:31.682
where the battle was being
waged.

00:42:31.749 --> 00:42:34.250
&gt;&gt; The fear inside this White
House is that China is using

00:42:34.317 --> 00:42:37.554
its vast financial resources
to leap ahead, technologically,

00:42:37.620 --> 00:42:39.089
of the United States.

00:42:39.156 --> 00:42:40.524
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The Trump
administration was trying

00:42:40.591 --> 00:42:43.560
to restrict China's access
to valuable technology

00:42:43.627 --> 00:42:45.128
developed by American companies.

00:42:45.195 --> 00:42:46.830
&gt;&gt; First up, though,
this morning,

00:42:46.897 --> 00:42:48.364
the Trump White House
announcing a pivot.

00:42:48.431 --> 00:42:51.901
&gt;&gt; Using existing law related
to national emergencies

00:42:51.968 --> 00:42:54.972
to restrict Chinese investment
in sensitive technologies.

00:42:55.039 --> 00:42:57.141
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: On Sand Hill Road,

00:42:57.207 --> 00:42:59.809
I met one of the most
experienced high-tech bankers

00:42:59.876 --> 00:43:05.015
in the valley, who was troubled
by what he was seeing.

00:43:05.082 --> 00:43:07.484
He told me about a flood of
calls he started receiving

00:43:07.551 --> 00:43:10.421
from Chinese investors
about five years ago.

00:43:10.487 --> 00:43:13.690
He remembered one Chinese
investor in particular.

00:43:13.757 --> 00:43:16.627
&gt;&gt; He'd been sent to invest
in technology; could I help?

00:43:16.693 --> 00:43:19.496
And I said, "Well, what kind
of technology?"

00:43:19.562 --> 00:43:23.133
And he, he had difficulty
answering the question.

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:26.336 line:0%
And if I pushed him hard,
clearly in the end,

00:43:26.403 --> 00:43:31.675 line:0%
it would be artificial
intelligence, semiconductors.

00:43:31.742 --> 00:43:34.478
Maybe things having to do with
automotive.

00:43:34.545 --> 00:43:36.480
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: The Chinese
government's top priorities.

00:43:36.546 --> 00:43:38.314
&gt;&gt; The Chinese government's top
priorities, right.

00:43:38.381 --> 00:43:42.452
And, and then I said, "Well,
how much do you have to invest?"

00:43:42.519 --> 00:43:45.889
And he claimed that he had
access to a billion dollars.

00:43:45.956 --> 00:43:48.158
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: A billion dollars?
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:43:48.225 --> 00:43:55.365
And then I met a private equity
firm that had $15 billion

00:43:55.432 --> 00:43:58.669
from some entity
in the Chinese government.

00:43:58.735 --> 00:44:00.504
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: How much money?
&gt;&gt; $15 billion.

00:44:00.571 --> 00:44:02.439
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: With a B.
&gt;&gt; Yeah, and they told me

00:44:02.505 --> 00:44:05.776
that their only,
their only mandate

00:44:05.843 --> 00:44:07.878
was to invest in semiconductors.

00:44:07.945 --> 00:44:09.779
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What did you think
of that?

00:44:09.846 --> 00:44:12.683
&gt;&gt; I thought, "This is...
I don't know if this is good."

00:44:12.749 --> 00:44:14.417
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: I mean, you've been
at the heart

00:44:14.484 --> 00:44:17.488
of Silicon Valley financing...
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:44:17.554 --> 00:44:19.623
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: For 35 years.
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:44:19.690 --> 00:44:21.191
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: What do you think
is happening here?

00:44:21.258 --> 00:44:24.328
&gt;&gt; I think China is doing
its absolute best

00:44:24.395 --> 00:44:26.563
to make itself self-sufficient,

00:44:26.630 --> 00:44:29.133
from a technological
point of view.

00:44:29.199 --> 00:44:32.602
They realize that in order
to accomplish that,

00:44:32.669 --> 00:44:36.640
they either have got to start
pedaling faster on their own,

00:44:36.707 --> 00:44:41.044
or they've got to buy
a lot of technology.

00:44:41.111 --> 00:44:43.246
(talking softly in background)

00:44:43.313 --> 00:44:45.982
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: That one.
Thank you.

00:44:46.049 --> 00:44:49.386
At Stanford University, I found
investors and entrepreneurs

00:44:49.453 --> 00:44:52.588
grappling with China's
high-tech ambitions.

00:44:52.655 --> 00:44:55.425 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Silicon Valley is very much
at the heart of the trade war.

00:44:55.491 --> 00:44:56.827 line:0%
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Why do you say
that?

00:44:56.894 --> 00:44:59.329 line:0%
&gt;&gt; The U.S. needs to keep
a technological advantage.

00:44:59.396 --> 00:45:02.466 line:0%
Silicon Valley, it's generating
a lot of the innovations

00:45:02.532 --> 00:45:05.702 line:0%
that are powering the U.S.,
in terms of all sorts

00:45:05.769 --> 00:45:07.237 line:0%
of different technologies.

00:45:07.304 --> 00:45:08.505
&gt;&gt; On this chart, in terms...

00:45:08.572 --> 00:45:10.741
&gt;&gt; Somebody from the business
community said,

00:45:10.808 --> 00:45:11.908
you know,
"We're not in a trade war,

00:45:11.975 --> 00:45:13.610
we're in a techonomic war."

00:45:13.677 --> 00:45:16.179 line:0%
And I think that's what we
probably

00:45:16.246 --> 00:45:17.614 line:0%
are really worried about.

00:45:17.681 --> 00:45:19.849 line:0%
&gt;&gt; A lot of Chinese
technology companies

00:45:19.916 --> 00:45:22.485 line:0%
invest heavily in 5Gs...

00:45:22.552 --> 00:45:25.555
&gt;&gt; Now there are areas where
they're actually, you know,

00:45:25.622 --> 00:45:28.691
quite competitive, and some
areas where they even seem to be

00:45:28.758 --> 00:45:30.327
maybe having an, an edge.

00:45:30.393 --> 00:45:32.162
&gt;&gt; And you know what?

00:45:32.229 --> 00:45:35.899
Chinese companies already
working on 6Gs.

00:45:35.965 --> 00:45:38.068
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Despite their
worries about China,

00:45:38.134 --> 00:45:41.071
people here also depend on
Chinese investments

00:45:41.137 --> 00:45:43.039
and were concerned that
the Trump administration

00:45:43.106 --> 00:45:44.841
would go too far.

00:45:44.908 --> 00:45:47.711 line:0%
Do you think the administration
had good reason

00:45:47.778 --> 00:45:51.047 line:0%
to clamp down on investments
from China in Silicon Valley?

00:45:51.114 --> 00:45:52.949 line:0%
&gt;&gt; I think so, but there's
a difference between,

00:45:53.016 --> 00:45:56.953 line:0%
"Yes, there's a problem," and
the response being measured,

00:45:57.020 --> 00:45:58.021 line:0%
appropriate, and grounded.

00:45:58.088 --> 00:45:59.189 line:0%
I think they, they may end up
operating

00:45:59.256 --> 00:46:00.924 line:0%
to our detriment broadly
economically, but also,

00:46:00.991 --> 00:46:02.692 line:0%
without the ability
to collaborate,

00:46:02.759 --> 00:46:06.229 line:0%
it's going to be very difficult
for the U.S. to keep up.

00:46:06.296 --> 00:46:08.965 line:0%
&gt;&gt; Business used to be the
ballast in the relationship,

00:46:09.032 --> 00:46:11.635 line:0%
because American companies
made money,

00:46:11.701 --> 00:46:16.039 line:0%
American consumers got cheap
goods, kept inflation down.

00:46:16.106 --> 00:46:18.274 line:0%
China got know-how, capital,
et cetera.

00:46:18.341 --> 00:46:21.577 line:0%
The business relationship is now
the major conflict,

00:46:21.644 --> 00:46:24.681
'cause we're both going for all
the technologies of the future.

00:46:24.748 --> 00:46:28.485
We're both racing for global
leadership influence.

00:46:28.552 --> 00:46:33.824
So now business is, is an
irritant, and it's the conflict.

00:46:33.891 --> 00:46:36.593
♪ ♪

00:46:36.660 --> 00:46:38.561
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: As I drove around
the valley,

00:46:38.628 --> 00:46:41.831
I could see the challenge
of this high-tech conflict.

00:46:41.898 --> 00:46:44.201
Chinese businesses
are visibly present,

00:46:44.267 --> 00:46:46.969
tightly connected
to the economy.

00:46:47.036 --> 00:46:49.072
And few people I met here

00:46:49.139 --> 00:46:50.607
thought the Trump
administration's hard line

00:46:50.673 --> 00:46:54.377
on China would be good for
anyone in the long run.

00:46:54.444 --> 00:46:56.646
&gt;&gt; The endgame here is the
decoupling

00:46:56.713 --> 00:46:58.348
of the American and Chinese
economies.

00:46:58.415 --> 00:47:00.217
&gt;&gt; Which, by the way, is already
underway,

00:47:00.284 --> 00:47:02.151
and it's going to continue.

00:47:02.218 --> 00:47:05.856
&gt;&gt; I think there are people who
think that sealing ourselves off

00:47:05.923 --> 00:47:08.759
is, is ultimately
the best solution.

00:47:08.825 --> 00:47:10.660
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: To break China and
the United States'

00:47:10.727 --> 00:47:13.530
economies apart.
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:47:13.596 --> 00:47:14.932
But that seems so sad,

00:47:14.998 --> 00:47:16.800
because we could do so much
for each other.

00:47:16.867 --> 00:47:19.803
If your goal is to stop China
from advancing,

00:47:19.870 --> 00:47:21.704
you're not going to accomplish
that anyway,

00:47:21.771 --> 00:47:24.807
because they'll, they'll just
innovate around you.

00:47:24.874 --> 00:47:27.243
Why would you want to stop
anybody from making progress?

00:47:27.310 --> 00:47:29.379
I, I don't see that.

00:47:29.446 --> 00:47:31.648
What I think our goal should be
is to...

00:47:31.715 --> 00:47:33.750
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Some people would
say because they could become

00:47:33.817 --> 00:47:36.252
more powerful in the
world marketplace

00:47:36.319 --> 00:47:37.353
than, than the United States.

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:39.823
&gt;&gt; The better goal is for us to
spend time

00:47:39.889 --> 00:47:42.359
on becoming more powerful
ourselves, I think.

00:47:42.426 --> 00:47:44.928
♪ ♪

00:47:44.994 --> 00:47:46.729
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: That was a
sentiment I'd been hearing

00:47:46.796 --> 00:47:49.365
throughout my reporting
on the trade war.

00:47:49.432 --> 00:47:51.367
And back in Ohio,
where I'd first seen

00:47:51.434 --> 00:47:52.869
the impact of the tariffs.

00:47:52.936 --> 00:47:55.305
&gt;&gt; The future is on the line for
more workers at General Motors.

00:47:55.372 --> 00:47:57.173
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: People were making
the same point

00:47:57.240 --> 00:48:00.476
in the face of seemingly
unstoppable economic forces.

00:48:00.543 --> 00:48:03.046
&gt;&gt; A large American factory
stopped production today...

00:48:03.113 --> 00:48:05.548
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Earlier this year,
the GM plant in Lordstown

00:48:05.615 --> 00:48:07.083
stopped producing cars...

00:48:07.150 --> 00:48:09.119
(horn honking, crowd shouting)

00:48:09.186 --> 00:48:10.954
the latest hit to auto workers.

00:48:12.188 --> 00:48:13.356 line:0%
&gt;&gt; This plant can't close.

00:48:13.423 --> 00:48:15.691 line:0%
When it first opened, it was the
largest plant

00:48:15.758 --> 00:48:17.260 line:0%
under one roof in the world.

00:48:17.327 --> 00:48:19.963
&gt;&gt; (chanting)

00:48:20.030 --> 00:48:21.965
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: With China
aggressively pursuing

00:48:22.032 --> 00:48:24.334
next-generation technology,

00:48:24.401 --> 00:48:27.637
the talk in Lordstown that day
was how this plant could be

00:48:27.704 --> 00:48:30.908
transformed to keep
the U.S. competitive.

00:48:30.974 --> 00:48:32.975
&gt;&gt; My personal hope
is that General Motors,

00:48:33.042 --> 00:48:37.713
which is investing billions
of dollars in all-electric,

00:48:37.780 --> 00:48:42.252
emission-free, green cars, will
decide to build them right here.

00:48:42.319 --> 00:48:43.653
(car horn honking)

00:48:43.719 --> 00:48:46.456
&gt;&gt; We've got to fix our system
to compete with China.

00:48:46.523 --> 00:48:48.425
We've got to internalize some of
this blame

00:48:48.491 --> 00:48:50.760
and not spend all our time
blaming it on China.

00:48:50.827 --> 00:48:52.529
They've outsmarted us, they've
done some things

00:48:52.595 --> 00:48:54.798
that we don't agree with,
they've done some things

00:48:54.865 --> 00:48:56.432
against the agreements
they've made,

00:48:56.499 --> 00:48:58.301
but they're focused
and moving ahead.

00:48:58.368 --> 00:49:00.036
&gt;&gt; China has a plan.

00:49:00.103 --> 00:49:02.472 line:0%
They got a ten-year, a 20-year,
a 50-year plan.

00:49:02.539 --> 00:49:05.642 line:0%
I mean, we really need to get
serious about this in,

00:49:05.709 --> 00:49:07.477 line:0%
in terms of electric vehicles,

00:49:07.544 --> 00:49:10.780 line:0%
in terms of, of new technology,
in terms of manufacturing,

00:49:10.847 --> 00:49:13.883 line:0%
and make sure that our
government is supportive.

00:49:13.950 --> 00:49:15.718
&gt;&gt; We didn't do
what China's doing.

00:49:15.785 --> 00:49:17.521
We didn't look at, "Where are
the industries of the future?

00:49:17.587 --> 00:49:19.956
Where do... what kind of
training do we need?

00:49:20.023 --> 00:49:21.892
What kind of people do we need?

00:49:21.958 --> 00:49:24.560
What kind of incentives do
business need to do this?"

00:49:24.627 --> 00:49:26.830
This is where, actually,
the Chinese system

00:49:26.897 --> 00:49:31.134
that we've always looked down on
actually has an advantage now.

00:49:31.201 --> 00:49:33.369
♪ ♪

00:49:33.436 --> 00:49:36.206
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Over the past
several weeks in Washington,

00:49:36.272 --> 00:49:38.508
President Trump has been upping
the pressure

00:49:38.575 --> 00:49:40.577
to get an agreement
on at least some

00:49:40.644 --> 00:49:43.380
of the long-standing issues.

00:49:43.447 --> 00:49:46.182
&gt;&gt; We are rounding the turn.

00:49:46.249 --> 00:49:47.784
We'll see what happens.

00:49:47.850 --> 00:49:50.286
We have a ways to go,
but not very far.

00:49:50.353 --> 00:49:52.789
&gt;&gt; What's still left to agree
to, sir?

00:49:52.855 --> 00:49:54.457
&gt;&gt; We have things,
we have things.

00:49:54.524 --> 00:49:58.561
We're talking
intellectual-property protection

00:49:58.628 --> 00:50:02.632
and theft, we're talking about
certain tariffs...

00:50:02.699 --> 00:50:06.269
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: Despite challenges,
he says a deal is possible.

00:50:06.336 --> 00:50:08.371
&gt;&gt; This is the granddaddy of
them all,

00:50:08.438 --> 00:50:10.474
and we'll see if it happens.

00:50:10.540 --> 00:50:12.542
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN:
But whether a deal is made,

00:50:12.609 --> 00:50:14.777
Trump's trade war has heightened
the economic conflict.

00:50:14.844 --> 00:50:18.814
&gt;&gt; I think I'll quote
my Chinese friends...

00:50:18.881 --> 00:50:22.385
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: And the specter of
a prolonged rivalry looms large.

00:50:22.452 --> 00:50:26.689
What does Trump want from China?

00:50:26.756 --> 00:50:28.558
What did the camp in the
White House that you were in,

00:50:28.625 --> 00:50:30.593
what do you want?

00:50:30.660 --> 00:50:33.697
&gt;&gt; I believe you need... you
need actually a change

00:50:33.763 --> 00:50:36.900
of the top leaders in the
Chinese Communist Party.

00:50:36.967 --> 00:50:39.536
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: How on Earth...
&gt;&gt; I think the goal

00:50:39.603 --> 00:50:41.705
into China is quite simply,
is to bring them...

00:50:41.771 --> 00:50:44.674
is to break the back
of this totalitarian

00:50:44.741 --> 00:50:47.277
mercantilist economic society...

00:50:47.344 --> 00:50:49.813
&gt;&gt; SULLIVAN: You're talking
about regime change.

00:50:49.879 --> 00:50:52.949
&gt;&gt; Well, first off,
nobody in the White House

00:50:53.016 --> 00:50:54.617
is talking about that, okay?

00:50:54.684 --> 00:50:56.686
And the president would never
even consider that.

00:50:56.753 --> 00:50:57.853
They're talking about a trade
deal

00:50:57.920 --> 00:50:59.556
and some fundamental economic
change.

00:50:59.622 --> 00:51:01.457
I'm saying, one of these two are
going to...

00:51:01.524 --> 00:51:03.526
this, either, this,
this mercantilist,

00:51:03.593 --> 00:51:06.296
totalitarian system that
has a network effect,

00:51:06.362 --> 00:51:09.432
or the kind of, you know,
liberal, democratic West.

00:51:09.499 --> 00:51:11.534
One of those two systems is
going to be the system

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:13.003
at the end of the day.

00:51:13.069 --> 00:51:15.371
(man speaking Chinese)

00:51:15.438 --> 00:51:19.442
&gt;&gt; Trade wars can get out of
control pretty fast.

00:51:19.509 --> 00:51:21.277
&gt;&gt; The arrest of a top executive
at Chinese telecom...

00:51:21.344 --> 00:51:23.646
&gt;&gt; This is really the United
States ramping things up

00:51:23.713 --> 00:51:25.381
against Huawei.

00:51:25.448 --> 00:51:26.883
&gt;&gt; Tensions in the South China
Sea escalate.

00:51:26.949 --> 00:51:29.085
&gt;&gt; Taiwan has become
a hot-button issue.

00:51:29.151 --> 00:51:32.455
&gt;&gt; Our next major war could be
fought against China.

00:51:32.521 --> 00:51:35.191
&gt;&gt; This is my optimistic
scenario,

00:51:35.258 --> 00:51:39.195
that we will have
a managed tension.

00:51:39.262 --> 00:51:43.934
But we do have the, uh,
pessimistic scenario.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:46.636
We do have a chance to see
a so-called...

00:51:46.703 --> 00:51:50.106
I don't like the term,
but the new cold war.

00:51:50.173 --> 00:51:54.010
I don't think like the one
the U.S. had with the USSR.

00:51:54.077 --> 00:51:57.613
But we will have another type of
cold war

00:51:57.680 --> 00:52:00.416
that nobody have ever
experienced.

00:52:00.483 --> 00:52:04.053
But I think it's a comprehensive
confrontation.

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:05.822
That's dangerous.

00:52:05.888 --> 00:52:08.958
That's really dangerous,
and if that happens,

00:52:09.024 --> 00:52:12.528
if that happens, it will last
for quite a long time.

00:52:12.595 --> 00:52:17.000
Then that's a tragedy
for everyone, I think.

